(210, 'com_content.article.5', '', '2022-12-17 11:07:24', 890, 8608, '382f26e28c2bcc29917ae4ca8ce89921bd7c9125', '{\"id\":\"5\",\"asset_id\":100,\"title\":\"Mnemonic\",\"alias\":\"mnemonic\",\"introtext\":\"<p><img src=\\\"images\\/mnemonic\\/xl-critical-thinking.jpg\\\" alt=\\\"xl critical thinking\\\" class=\\\"width-50\\\" style=\\\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\\\" \\/><\\/p>\\r\\n<h1 style=\\\"text-align: center;\\\">What is a mnemonic device?<\\/h1>\\r\\n<p>&nbsp;<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>A mnemonic device, also known as a mnemonic, is a learning technique that helps learners of all ages to retain or retrieve information. In other words, they\\u2019re a handy and effective way to boost your memory and to help you store important information that would otherwise be hard to remember.<\\/p>\\r\\n<h3>Where does the term mnemonic come from?<\\/h3>\\r\\n<p>The word mnemonic originally comes from \\u2018<em>mn\\u0113monikos\\u2019,<\\/em>&nbsp;an Ancient Greek word that refers to memory. The Ancient Greeks also worshipped Mnemosyne, who is the goddess of memory in Greek mythology. Even today, the term \\u2018mnemonic\\u2019 is frequently used when we\\u2019re talking about memory and the study of memory!<\\/p>\\r\\n<h3>Why do mnemonics help with memory?<\\/h3>\\r\\n<p>We\\u2019ve defined mnemonic devices, but why are they so effective?<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>Well, much of it has to do with how our brains store information. While the human brain can be an incredible storage device, it\\u2019s less well suited to storing loads of meaningless information. Instead, we\\u2019re much better at building connections between new information and previous knowledge, as well as at remembering images and phrases.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>Mnemonic devices are effective because they tap into the way our brains store information. Using mnemonics, we can encode information by turning it into a rhyme, sequence or even an easy-to-remember piece of imagery. Plus, this makes it much easier for us to retrieve it in the future.<\\/p>\\r\\n<h3>What are the different types of mnemonic device?<\\/h3>\\r\\n<p>One of the best things about mnemonics is that they can exist in a variety of different forms. These include:<\\/p>\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n<li>imagery<\\/li>\\r\\n<li>acronyms<\\/li>\\r\\n<li>rhymes<\\/li>\\r\\n<li>chunking<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n<p>To name but a few! This means the mnemonic type that your learners choose might depend on their learning style. For instance, who want to learn visually might use a metaphor or a mental image to remember key information. On the other hand, a kinaesthetic learner might remember something using a certain gesture.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>In this next bit, we\\u2019ll go into more detail about some of the different kinds of mnemonic device:<\\/p>\\r\\n<p><strong>Imagery and visualization<\\/strong><\\/p>\\r\\n<p>Images can be much easier to remember than big chunks of information or large passages of text, which makes them excellent mnemonic devices. We simply need to translate facts and information into memorable mental images.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>For example, if you are trying to learn a new language, you might benefit from creating mental images from some vocabulary words:<\\/p>\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n<li>The Spanish word for tiger is tigre, so you could imagine a&nbsp;grey tiger drinking tea.<\\/li>\\r\\n<li>The Spanish word for sun is sol, so you could imagine that&nbsp;the sun is burning the sole of your foot.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n<p>&nbsp;<\\/p>\\r\\n<p><strong>Acronyms and acrostics<\\/strong><\\/p>\\r\\n<p>An&nbsp;<a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.twinkl.de\\/teaching-wiki\\/acronym\\\">acronym<\\/a>&nbsp;is a word or phrase formed by using the first letter(s) of the items you want to remember. They can make fantastic mnemonic devices because they allow us to condense multiple things down into one easy-to-remember phrase!<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>For example, to be able to recall the colours of the rainbow, you could use the acronym ROYGIBIV - red, orange, yellow, green, blue, indigo and violet. Plus, by using the same example of the colours of the rainbow, we can create an acrostic:<\\/p>\\r\\n<p><strong>R<\\/strong>ichard&nbsp;<strong>o<\\/strong>f&nbsp;<strong>Y<\\/strong>ork&nbsp;<strong>g<\\/strong>ave&nbsp;<strong>b<\\/strong>attle&nbsp;<strong>i<\\/strong>n&nbsp;<strong>v<\\/strong>ain.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>This acronym is a particularly good one because we can use it to remember history as well as colours. That\\u2019s because it\\u2019s also talking about the ill-fated English king Richard III, who took part in the Battle of Bosworth Field in 1485. Notice how it condenses the key facts about what happened at the battle into one easy-to-remember acronym.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p><strong>Rhyme<\\/strong><\\/p>\\r\\n<p>Rhymes are great as mnemonic devices. They use rhythm and \'acoustic encoding\' to make concepts easier to remember. This means that phrases which \'roll off the tongue\' are easier to remember because they are appealing to our brains.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>Here is a rhyming mnemonic you might know:<\\/p>\\r\\n<p><em>I before e, except after c,<\\/em><\\/p>\\r\\n<p><em>And when sounding like a<\\/em><\\/p>\\r\\n<p><em>As in neighbour and weigh.<\\/em><\\/p>\\r\\n<p>This mnemonic is particularly helpful when trying to remember the position and pronunciation of the letter \\u2018e\\u2019 in a word. By referring back to this mnemonic, we\\u2019ll be able to figure out that \'ei\' is often used after the letter \'c\' in words like \'deceive\' and \'ceiling\'.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p><strong>Chunking<\\/strong><\\/p>\\r\\n<p>As the name suggests, chunking is a tool that lets us store information by breaking it down into small, easy-to-recall \\u2018chunks\\u2019. Since our brains can only process so much information at one time, these devices are great for helping us to simplify complex information.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>A good example, and one that we use every day without realizing it, is phone numbers. Even though they form one long number, you\\u2019ll often see them being written down in two or three more manageable chunks.<\\/p>\\r\\n<h3>When might we use mnemonics?<\\/h3>\\r\\n<p>While mnemonics are useful for pretty much everyone.In this next section, you\\u2019ll find some common and popular examples that children will likely use in school to remember key information. In fact, there\\u2019s a good chance that you will have used some of them yourself!<\\/p>\\r\\n<p><strong>For the order of a list<\\/strong><\\/p>\\r\\n<p>Instead of simply memorizing a list, you can come up with an inventive way of remembering it. If the mnemonic device is humorous, then there\\u2019s a better chance you\\u2019ll be able to recall it. For example, take a look at this mnemonic for remembering the distance of the planets in our solar system from the sun:<\\/p>\\r\\n<p><strong>M<\\/strong>y&nbsp;<strong>V<\\/strong>ery&nbsp;<strong>E<\\/strong>ducated&nbsp;<strong>M<\\/strong>other&nbsp;<strong>J<\\/strong>ust&nbsp;<strong>S<\\/strong>erved&nbsp;<strong>U<\\/strong>s&nbsp;<strong>N<\\/strong>achos<\\/p>\\r\\n<p><strong>M<\\/strong>ercury&nbsp;<strong>V<\\/strong>enus&nbsp;<strong>E<\\/strong>arth&nbsp;<strong>M<\\/strong>ars&nbsp;<strong>J<\\/strong>upiter&nbsp;<strong>S<\\/strong>aturn&nbsp;<strong>U<\\/strong>ranus&nbsp;<strong>N<\\/strong>eptune<\\/p>\\r\\n<p><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.twinkl.de\\/resource\\/t2-s-409-mnemonic-solar-system-planets-display-banner-detailed-images\\\"><\\/a><\\/p>\",\"fulltext\":\"\",\"state\":\"1\",\"catid\":2,\"created\":\"2022-10-24 20:04:38\",\"created_by\":\"890\",\"created_by_alias\":\"\",\"modified\":\"2022-12-17 11:07:24\",\"modified_by\":890,\"checked_out\":890,\"checked_out_time\":\"2022-12-17 11:06:43\",\"publish_up\":\"2022-10-24 20:04:38\",\"publish_down\":null,\"images\":\"{\\\"image_intro\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"image_intro_alt\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"float_intro\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"image_intro_caption\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"image_fulltext\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"image_fulltext_alt\\\":\\\"